The lattes took over 20 minutes after we ordered and were basically just warmed milk so we asked for an extra black coffee to top them off with and it didn't even change the flavor. Our food took almost an hour and only the sandwich was warm. My friend who ordered the avocado toast couldn't even eat all of it even though we hadn't eaten today yet because it was so bad. As we were finishing our meal another patron yelled that if anyone was there that wrote restaurant reviews to give this place a terrible review. As we were leaving we considered warning all the people that waiting to not waste their time there. This was probably one of my top five worst restaurant experiences.

We came here for lunch after visiting Minutemen National Park. The food was tasty and the staff were friendly, but I was concerned about the lack of social distancing with the seating arrangements. Yes, the staff were all wearing masks and there was hand sanitiser everywhere. However, halfway during our meal they seated a party of six adults on the other side of the picnic table we were on. There’s a plastic barrier separating the two halves of the table on the tabletop, but not for the seats. We shifted as far to the end of our side of the table as possible, but even as two adults and two small children there was probably only 2 ft of space between us and the other party. All the other tables we could see looked pretty busy by then and we’d nearly finished, so we didn’t bother asking to move tables and just finished as quickly as we could.  Sharing tables in Covid times is problematic enough, without trying to squeeze ten people on one table when they’re not in the same party. Probably two couples on far ends is as close as is safe on those things. I probably won’t be back as a result, which is a shame given the food was nice.

Great ambiance & food in an historic general store converted into a restaurant. Sandwiches are ample & served on terrific, fresh baked bread. Try their sweet, home baked, cornbread- it's DELICIOUS!  The menu is varied in offerings & price, so usually something for everyone. The BLT comes made on huge slices of the home-made bread & hamburgers are quite tasty. There's also lots of fancier fare, so there's sufficient choice. Flavored hot coffee is always available & bakery items are EXCELLENT - especially the cookies & gingerbread!  Staff can be great or substandard, particularly the younger waitresses who are aggressive about taking tables, but have insufficient training or skills to service them. Attribute inconsistencies in service to erratic, inefficient, management. And, know it's not personal, so shrug off the often rude or disinterested servers & be prepared to ask for something multiple times - it's pot luck when it comes to service, counter take-out or table.  Lunchtime seems to be their busiest time, so expect a little wait, whether dining in or doing take-out.  There is pretty outdoor seating, too, if you don't mind purchasing your food & walking w/ it outside & around to the back of the restaurant. Because this is an OLD building, access to outdoor seating is a little maze-like.  Amazing live music is offered weekly; with limited seating capacity, expect the place to be packed, but, worthwhile. Reserving a table ahead of time is a smart option.  Finally, if seated inside, do make sure to appreciate the charming framed pictures & newspaper clippings offering glimpses into yesteryear ;)

3 Strikes – 3 different visits over 3 different seasons at 3 different times for 3 different meals – all failures  I make it a point to support independent businesses whenever I can.  Unfortunately, Main Streets isn’t worth it.  Now I know what other residents have been complaining about.  My recent experiences at Main Streets have been horrible.  The only bright spot is if you sit at the bar.  The bartender is great.  She is polite, competent, efficient, and pleasant – all the things her colleagues aren’t.  My family and I will be avoiding Main Streets and I suggest you do the same.  There are other more worthy restaurants in town who appreciate their customers.  My most 3 most recent experiences are below.  July 2019 – Strike 3 - Given my previous bad experiences dining here for lunch and dinner (see below), I decided to try Main Streets one last time by ordering take out.  This was another failure.  I called my order in and was told it would be ready in 10-20 minutes.  I arrived 18 minutes later.  My order hadn’t even been put it.  The staff offered to put my order in and have it rushed.  I declined.  The last thing I wanted was rushed, ill-prepared food and to wait another 20 minutes.  May 2019 – Strike 2 – I was meeting a colleague at Main Streets for a quick business lunch.  I arrived early to get a table so we could get in and get out.  Even though there was plenty of room in the dining room, the waitress didn’t want to seat us.  She wanted to put us in the burrito bar.  Having been to the burrito bar previously, I didn’t want to sit there again.  It’s not a conducive setting for a business/nice lunch.  After discussing this for some time with the waitress, I finally pointed out that my colleague and I would be eating for the same amount of time, 1 hour, as most of their other patrons.  So, what was the problem with sitting in the dining room, especially since there was plenty of space?  March 2019 – Strike 1 - Three other dads and I went to Main Streets for a beer at 8:45 PM.  There was plenty of space available, so we picked a table for 4 in the bar area.  The waitress came over and asked what we wanted to eat.  We told her we only wanted beers.  She told us that even though there was only 15 minutes before the kitchen closed and even though there was plenty of empty tables, all of the tables were only for patrons ordering food.  We said okay, we’ll look at the menu.  We ordered 4 beers.  When she came back, we told her we’d like the nachos.  She rudely said, “Is that all?”  Since we didn’t even want the nachos and we ordered them just to pacify her, we told her we didn’t want anything else.  She again mentioned that these tables were only for dinner and stormed off.  After this rudeness, we each had our beer and left.
